A business provides you with the following data and wants you to find patterns in their customer's habits so that they can make better recommendations and target certain groups in the future.

Would we approach this as a supervised or unsupervised learning task and why?

We would approach this as a supervised learning task because we have "correct" data we can work off of, and we can see how different features will affect our target variable "spending score".

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.datasets import make_blobs

wcss = []
for i in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, init='k-means++', max_iter=300, n_init=10, random_state=0)
    kmeans.fit(newdf)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# Plotting the elbow curve
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
plt.plot(range(1, 11), wcss, marker='o')
plt.title('Elbow Method')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('WCSS')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

In [46]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import scipy.cluster.hierarchy as sch
from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering


dendrogram = sch.dendrogram(sch.linkage(newdf, method='ward'))

threshold = 150  # Example threshold for demonstration
plt.axhline(color='r', linestyle='--')
plt.title('Dendrogram with Cluster Separation')
plt.xlabel('Index')
plt.ylabel('Distance')

model = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=None, linkage='ward', distance_threshold=threshold)
model.fit(newdf)
newdf['Cluster'] = model.labels_

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
for cluster_label in newdf['Cluster'].unique():
    cluster_data = newdf[newdf['Cluster'] == cluster_label]
    plt.scatter(cluster_data['Annual Income (k$)'], cluster_data['Spending Score (1-100)'], label=f'Cluster {cluster_label}')

plt.title('Clusters of Hierarchical Clustering')
plt.xlabel('Annual Income (k$)')
plt.ylabel('Spending Score (1-100)')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

it appears that heirarchical clustering produces very similar results to kmeans clustering, however, we can see that cluster 1 has obtained more data points within its radius as opposed to kmeans. We can see that kmeans cares more about having equal, but very distinct clusters of data to identify. Heirarchical clustering is tree based, and as a result, will seek to find more nuanced a detailed patterns within our data outside of just a distance metric, hence, why it is showing extra samples in cluster 1.

With this being said, I would recommend using kmeans clustering for most general purposes, because it is a fairly simple algorithm that is useful in classifying future samples, and works well with data that is already pre-classified, hence, being a supervised algorithm. Its performance is also much better than heirarchical clustering because of how simple its algorithm is.

Perhaps predicting what "genre" of "spender" a new person would be is a good example of what we can use kmeans clustering for.

Heirarchical clustering is useful because it does not require the elbow method to acquire the optimal cluster count, as it doesn't really need any parameters or specified info regardless.

Heirarchical clustering would do its best when we have a small(er) dataset with NO expectations on how the data will be clustered. Heirarchical is useful for finding indepth, hard-to-spot trends within data.

I would recommend heirarchical clustering if we had no idea what to expect from our annual income to spending score graph. Heirarchical clustering would do well to expose these trends and give us needed insight to explore data that we have no info to work with.
